{"term":"1973","caseName":"Kahn v. Shevin","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1973/73-78","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 26, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/15961","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume arguments in 73-78.","start":0,"stop":8.484,"duration":8.48},{"text":"Mr. McKenzie.","start":8.484,"stop":16.884,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court.","start":16.884,"stop":20.185,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Because of that part of the argument yesterday, I feel that it’s necessary this time to clarify some of the facts of this case.","start":20.185,"stop":30.404,"duration":10.22},{"text":"This is a claim by a widower that he has been denied equal protection of the law both by a mandatory, self-executing provision of a Florida constitution and by a statute providing exemption from ad valorem taxation of properties with a value of $500 yearly for widows but not for widowers.","start":30.404,"stop":53.074,"duration":22.67},{"text":"Now, that’s important for two reasons.","start":53.074,"stop":55.284,"duration":2.21},{"text":"One, first of all, counsel in argument yesterday stated that this was a deduction from taxation.","start":55.284,"stop":64.62,"duration":9.34},{"text":"In fact, it’s not a deduction.","start":64.62,"stop":65.977,"duration":1.36},{"text":"It’s an exemption to the amount of $500 which, in dollar terms translated through the assessment laws of Florida, comes out to about a $15 amount.","start":65.977,"stop":83.689,"duration":17.71},{"text":"Secondly, --","start":83.689,"stop":84.359,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What difference does that make?","start":84.359,"stop":86.401,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"We don’t make a de minimis argument.","start":86.401,"stop":88.007,"duration":1.61},{"text":"I simply wanted to clarify the fact that it’s not a $500 deduction from tax but --","start":88.007,"stop":94.876,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you were making a distinction between a deduction and an exemption.","start":94.876,"stop":97.989,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":97.989,"stop":99.485,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And I ask, is there a difference?","start":99.485,"stop":101.527,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there is a difference.","start":101.527,"stop":103.057,"duration":1.53},{"text":"The exemption--","start":103.057,"stop":103.216,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If there’s a difference, is there a significant --","start":103.216,"stop":104.398,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The exemption is from the ad valorem value of the property.","start":104.398,"stop":108.677,"duration":4.28},{"text":"In other words, if property is worth --","start":108.677,"stop":110.488,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know what it is, but I’m asking what difference does it make?","start":110.488,"stop":113.07,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It makes a difference --","start":113.07,"stop":114.37,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It makes a difference about $485.","start":114.37,"stop":116.388,"duration":2.02},{"text":"Is that right?","start":116.388,"stop":116.955,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, Your Honor.","start":116.955,"stop":118.012,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But what legal difference does it make is what I’m trying to --","start":118.012,"stop":121.223,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"No legal difference as far as this particular case.","start":121.223,"stop":123.912,"duration":2.69},{"text":"I merely wanted to clarify the fact, Your Honor.","start":123.912,"stop":126.961,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Secondly --","start":126.961,"stop":128.396,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s a $15-benefit.","start":128.396,"stop":129.425,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s a $15-benefit and I was merely trying to put it in perspective.","start":129.425,"stop":133.217,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually, if the $500 were actually deductible from the taxable you refer to it as a tax credit, wouldn’t you?","start":133.217,"stop":140.21,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":140.21,"stop":142.192,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yesterday, we had another case involving all kinds of millions of claims $3-10, but the case was here just as well.","start":142.192,"stop":150.469,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, and we’re not making an argument that the case should not be here.","start":150.469,"stop":156.065,"duration":5.6},{"text":"The other question --","start":156.065,"stop":156.964,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m sure you’d rather that it weren’t.","start":156.964,"stop":159.71,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":159.71,"stop":161.627,"duration":1.92},{"text":"The other question though is of more significance and that’s the fact that we are dealing with, as I say, not simply a statute but a provision of the Florida constitution.","start":161.627,"stop":174.926,"duration":13.3},{"text":"And this is significant in that, as we noted in our brief, we know of no case providing for this Court or the Florida Court to expand a provision of the constitution to include members of a class who are not included in the class where there is no ambiguity, and I think that’s important in the discussion yesterday of whether it could be sent back to the Florida Supreme Court for the purpose of expanding the class in the statute.","start":174.926,"stop":210.656,"duration":35.73},{"text":"It isn’t simply a statute.","start":210.656,"stop":212.738,"duration":2.08},{"text":"It’s a Florida constitutional provision that we’re dealing with.","start":212.738,"stop":215.836,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand it, the ultimate conclusion was that Mrs. Ginsburg, I think, acknowledged that that wasn’t for us to do that.","start":215.836,"stop":226.778,"duration":10.94},{"text":"The limit of our function here was to uphold the provision of the Florida constitution and statute or to invalidate it and, if it’s invalidated, it would be remanded to the Florida Supreme Court to do with our decision what it will.","start":226.778,"stop":243.321,"duration":16.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Very good.","start":243.321,"stop":244.037,"duration":0.72},{"text":"They’ve made a strong argument in their briefs --","start":244.037,"stop":246.555,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As to what the Supreme Court ought to do, but that’s not for us.","start":246.555,"stop":251.019,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Basically, the State of Florida has two positions.","start":251.019,"stop":254.344,"duration":3.32},{"text":"First of all, that the compelling interest tests of the Frontiero plurality should not be applied to sex classifications and, secondly, that the classification of widows to the exclusion of widowers in view of the purpose and the factual realities of this situation does not, as applied to the appellant here, violate the equal protection either,-- whether tested by Frontiero in the plurality or by the standard in Reed, if in fact that’s different from traditional standards, or by traditional tax classification in sex standards.","start":254.344,"stop":293.501,"duration":39.16},{"text":"And I’ll address myself first to the traditional test because I feel that, under that test, it’s clear that the distinction here meets the test.","start":293.501,"stop":304.521,"duration":11.02},{"text":"First of all, the classification we have is a classification of widows and widowers, and the question is, what is the purpose of that classification?","start":304.521,"stop":317.11,"duration":12.59},{"text":"The State of Florida, as noted by the Florida Supreme Court, recognizes by this classification that women and especially widows are an economically disadvantaged class in our society.","start":317.11,"stop":329.904,"duration":12.79},{"text":"This is not in line with past cases where stereotypes were developed for the purpose of so-called protective legislation for denying women something on a basis of a stereotype that wasn’t backed up by facts but was backed up by beliefs that people had, by mythology, really.","start":329.904,"stop":355.463,"duration":25.56},{"text":"It’s not based --","start":355.463,"stop":356.303,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)economically disadvantaged?","start":356.303,"stop":358.695,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":358.695,"stop":359.387,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Widows.","start":359.387,"stop":359.844,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Widows?","start":359.844,"stop":360.511,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Widows, yes, I would say that widows is --","start":360.511,"stop":362.177,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the statistics were all over the country.","start":362.177,"stop":366.134,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The statistics of the country -- the widows are to the country -- I think the widows are economically disadvantaged.","start":366.134,"stop":371.599,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Anything but an economically disadvantaged.","start":371.599,"stop":374.131,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think my brother Brennan is referring to the fact that widows own a great deal of the property in the country but that is because there are many, many, many more widows than there are widowers.","start":374.131,"stop":386.578,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":386.578,"stop":386.973,"duration":0.4},{"text":"I would agree with that.","start":386.973,"stop":389.842,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And it’s somewhat those are --","start":389.842,"stop":391.788,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they--","start":391.788,"stop":392.228,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- don’t have any money and others do.","start":392.228,"stop":394.229,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that --","start":394.229,"stop":395.223,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Like widowers.","start":395.223,"stop":396.205,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I think-- but, basically, the fact is that taking a widow and a widower, the general facts are that a widow has a likelihood if she must transfer into the job market of not being able to earn as much as the widower simply, if for no other reason, then the fact is that women in general can only earn -- are only earning 60% of what men earn.","start":396.205,"stop":425.615,"duration":29.41}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean they are discriminated against?","start":425.615,"stop":426.97,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"They are discriminated against, and I think it’s a recognition of that fact.","start":426.97,"stop":432.101,"duration":5.13},{"text":"The Florida statute really wrecking and constitutional provision merely recognizes the women not because of any inherent problem with women but with an inherent problem with our society that hasn’t been corrected yet are, in fact, discriminated against.","start":432.101,"stop":449.376,"duration":17.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Does Florida give any other provision in benefit of women in their taxation other than this?","start":449.376,"stop":457.244,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Other than this particular --","start":457.244,"stop":458.841,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":458.841,"stop":459.553,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Provision?","start":459.553,"stop":461.396,"duration":1.84},{"text":"I’m not --","start":461.396,"stop":461.6,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Because I would assume that the widow before she becomes a widow, if what you say is true, she suffers a lot too.","start":461.6,"stop":467.889,"duration":6.29},{"text":"Does Florida recognize that in this taxing scheme?","start":467.889,"stop":471.103,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Women other than widowers?","start":471.103,"stop":472.365,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":472.365,"stop":473.52,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not familiar with any provisions that --","start":473.52,"stop":474.908,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why single out the widows?","start":474.908,"stop":476.851,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was the wills of people in adopting the constitution of Florida.","start":476.851,"stop":480.653,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our fact says when the constitution was adopted the same as they are today?","start":480.653,"stop":486.32,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon, Your Honor?","start":486.32,"stop":487.811,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Were women allowed to make contracts when this constitution was first adopted?","start":487.811,"stop":490.932,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"This constitution was adopted in 1968, Your Honor.","start":490.932,"stop":494.068,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn’t there a provision before then in the old constitution?","start":494.068,"stop":499.023,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":499.023,"stop":500.208,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And it was just carried over.","start":500.208,"stop":502.434,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It was --","start":502.434,"stop":503.126,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"When was it originally in the constitution?","start":503.126,"stop":504.706,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"1885, Your Honor.","start":504.706,"stop":506.54,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, aren’t women in a little disposition now than they were in 1885, little?","start":506.54,"stop":511.007,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"In a better position now than they were in 1885?","start":511.007,"stop":512.397,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":512.397,"stop":512.952,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":512.952,"stop":513.58,"duration":0.63},{"text":"But, clearly, they are not by any means have been given economic equality in society, and I think this is a recognition of that.","start":513.58,"stop":522.597,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But how can you put them in a class?","start":522.597,"stop":525.398,"duration":2.8},{"text":"I would assume that there are some widows in the Palm Beach area that are little better off than some widowers in upper part of Florida.","start":525.398,"stop":535.84,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the law has always recognized that no class is going to be perfect even if we took $4,000 limen than anyone who earns $4,000 or less should get $500 exemption but still have the --","start":535.84,"stop":550.913,"duration":15.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s especially true in taxation I assume.","start":550.913,"stop":554.093,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":554.093,"stop":554.685,"duration":0.59},{"text":"We still have the problem of saying that there are people who earn $4,000 who have no dependents and there are people who earn $4,001 who have 10 dependents and are much more needy.","start":554.685,"stop":568.648,"duration":13.96},{"text":"Obviously, for the purpose of taxation, states have never been called on to treat every case on an individual basis.","start":568.648,"stop":576.153,"duration":7.5},{"text":"And, I think that --","start":576.153,"stop":577.148,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course --","start":577.148,"stop":577.303,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court will recognize that that’s not a practical possibility.","start":577.303,"stop":580.637,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m just trying to get the reason for this singling out.","start":580.637,"stop":586.368,"duration":5.73},{"text":"You agree this is solely on sex?","start":586.368,"stop":591.135,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say it's sex as tied to economic reality.","start":591.135,"stop":595.743,"duration":4.61},{"text":"In other words, the class is not simply actually --","start":595.743,"stop":597.325,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s strictly, well --","start":597.325,"stop":598.683,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The fact, the class isn’t--","start":598.683,"stop":599.498,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This isn’t between a widow and a widower other than sex.","start":599.498,"stop":602.823,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Other than sex?","start":602.823,"stop":603.698,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":603.698,"stop":605.308,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"One, the fact that a widower being a man is recognized as having greater earning potential in our society --","start":605.308,"stop":611.442,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any way for a widower to become a widow?","start":611.442,"stop":614.514,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":614.514,"stop":615.242,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"There’s no way for a widower to become a widow.","start":615.242,"stop":619.683,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there is no way --","start":619.683,"stop":620.112,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"So, it’s sex.","start":620.112,"stop":622.156,"duration":2.04},{"text":"What’s wrong with admitting that it’s based on sex?","start":622.156,"stop":624.989,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s based -- Let’s say that it’s based on sex is accurate, but it’s based on sex plus an underlying recognition of factual difference between the sexes are not simply a stereotype difference between men and women.","start":624.989,"stop":641.294,"duration":16.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The same constitution also that prevented women from serving on juries, didn’t it?","start":641.294,"stop":645.986,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it did, Your Honor.","start":645.986,"stop":648.071,"duration":2.09},{"text":"The law of Florida prevented women from serving on juries.","start":648.071,"stop":650.822,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And now they do.","start":650.822,"stop":651.458,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"But it didn’t prevent them from showing on juries.","start":651.458,"stop":653.832,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, they’ve been persuaded to let women serve on juries, haven’t they?","start":653.832,"stop":656.68,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Women were not prevented from serving on juries.","start":656.68,"stop":659.829,"duration":3.15},{"text":"They had to take affirmative action to indicate a desire to serve on juries.","start":659.829,"stop":665.358,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Back in the 19th century?","start":665.358,"stop":669.298,"duration":3.94},{"text":"In the original --","start":669.298,"stop":669.758,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time of the Hoyt case, Your Honor.","start":669.758,"stop":671.873,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"In time of the original constitution?","start":671.873,"stop":674.326,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time the original constitution of Florida.","start":674.326,"stop":676.256,"duration":1.93},{"text":"I’m not prepared to say, Your Honor.","start":676.256,"stop":679.296,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKenzie, are you suggesting that this is based on economic need?","start":679.296,"stop":684.744,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":684.744,"stop":685.196,"duration":0.45},{"text":"I’m suggesting that this case is very little and different than Gruenwald versus Gardner which was --","start":685.196,"stop":689.286,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if it was based on economic need, why doesn’t it say so instead of putting it on widowhood?","start":689.286,"stop":697.559,"duration":8.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because I think it recognizes the underlying rationale.","start":697.559,"stop":701.983,"duration":4.42},{"text":"The class is not simply widows.","start":701.983,"stop":703.898,"duration":1.92},{"text":"The class is widows, the blind, and the totally and permanently disabled.","start":703.898,"stop":711.126,"duration":7.23},{"text":"I think that all those have the same line of reasoning running through them for different reasons.","start":711.126,"stop":717.281,"duration":6.15},{"text":"But disabled or --","start":717.281,"stop":717.377,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And the works --","start":717.377,"stop":718.428,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"All are economically disabled.","start":718.428,"stop":720.058,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It works to benefit the wealthy widow in Palm Beach.","start":720.058,"stop":725.103,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It works to benefit the wealthy --","start":725.103,"stop":727.99,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Widow and --","start":727.99,"stop":728.765,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Blind person also.","start":728.765,"stop":730.377,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The wealthy widow in Palm Beach and to disadvantage the poor spinster in Tallahassee.","start":730.377,"stop":735.333,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, but the fact is that, as a general objective analysis, women and widows are not in the same economic classification as our widowers.","start":735.333,"stop":755.336,"duration":20},{"text":"They don’t have the same opportunities.","start":755.336,"stop":757.337,"duration":2},{"text":"First of all, a woman who is a widow is either one of two possibilities.","start":757.337,"stop":763.223,"duration":5.89},{"text":"One, she’s the head of the household, the same as the widower and, in that case, the distinction is exactly as I’ve said that she has to -- she does not have, as a general rule, the job opportunity that the male does.","start":763.223,"stop":780.518,"duration":17.3},{"text":"The other case is where she has been -- she has not been the head of the household and a widow -- then the husband is the one that dies.","start":780.518,"stop":788.629,"duration":8.11},{"text":"And, in that case, she not only has to move over into the job market but she has to get someone to replace her and take over the duties that she had, which is really a double burden compared to the man whose wife dies who simply has to replace the functions that his wife had in the family unit.","start":788.629,"stop":808.226,"duration":19.6},{"text":"She has to do both that and move over into the job market.","start":808.226,"stop":812.499,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And if she moves over in the job market for the first time at age 55, I suppose her lower earnings compared to a widower who may have been in the market for 30 years aren’t necessarily attributable to discrimination.","start":812.499,"stop":825.434,"duration":12.93},{"text":"She simply hasn’t been in the market.","start":825.434,"stop":826.551,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"She hasn’t -- well, I would agree that they aren’t -- that that’s true but they’re even compounded by discrimination and that the job opportunities not only to an elderly person but to her particularly are greatly lessened both by her age and by her sex.","start":826.551,"stop":848.895,"duration":22.34},{"text":"Now, as to the general classification, the traditional test, first of all, if the Court is to use that test, then we would submit that it would be appropriate in all the tax cases where there are tax classifications, there’s a presumption of constitutionality, a heavy burden on one challenging the classification to show no conceivable permissible basis and it’s been recognized that the classification need not be exact or have mathematical nicety.","start":848.895,"stop":889.225,"duration":40.33},{"text":"Clearly, if the no conceivable rationale purpose test is to be used, I’d submit that the appellant here has not met that burden.","start":889.225,"stop":903.021,"duration":13.8},{"text":"Not only is there a conceivable rational purpose, I submit, but the purpose that we’ve offered to the court is in accordance with proper tax purpose concerned for the economically disadvantaged groups in society, and that that’s a valid social concern.","start":903.021,"stop":923.435,"duration":20.41},{"text":"Secondly, under Reed versus Reed, it’s possible that that case could be read to say that there is an additional burden that the court is going to place on the state where it makes a classification, and that’s the burden of justifying a rational classification.","start":923.435,"stop":946.418,"duration":22.98},{"text":"And, I submit again that we have not relied on stereotypes that women are either physically not capable of doing the work that men are capable of doing or the women are in some way, because they’re the creator of children, that they should stay at home.","start":946.418,"stop":971.134,"duration":24.72},{"text":"We’re not saying that.","start":971.134,"stop":971.968,"duration":0.83},{"text":"We believe that women have all the rights that men have, but that the facts of our society are that women have not yet been given those economic rights and that, until they do, it’s appropriate for the State of Florida to have legislation which recognizes that and gives them an affirmative chance to pull themselves to attain equality.","start":971.968,"stop":996.194,"duration":24.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Of $15?","start":996.194,"stop":1000.014,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the fact that it’s a small amount is true.","start":1000.014,"stop":1005.983,"duration":5.97},{"text":"But, to argue that the State of Florida should give more, the determination of the people of Florida was that it was an appropriate --","start":1005.983,"stop":1015.747,"duration":9.76}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Gesture.","start":1015.747,"stop":1016.353,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Gesture, and it is the --","start":1016.353,"stop":1017.832,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It might enable her to retain the ownership of the property rather than make a distressed sale of it.","start":1017.832,"stop":1021.649,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The fact is that someone at a low level of income, $15 -","start":1021.649,"stop":1026.273,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, $15 annually on taxes on a real estate.","start":1026.273,"stop":1027.571,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Annually, may enable them to retain property which they would otherwise not be able --","start":1027.571,"stop":1035.239,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"To sell.","start":1035.239,"stop":1035.603,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to retain.","start":1035.603,"stop":1038.63,"duration":3.03},{"text":"While we submit that the plurality opinion in Frontiero, Frontiero should not be applied.","start":1038.63,"stop":1051.777,"duration":13.15},{"text":"I would submit that based on that decision, the classification that we’ve established is sufficient.","start":1051.777,"stop":1062.153,"duration":10.38},{"text":"That case specifically, in a footnote, refers to in footnote 22 I believe it is, states it should be noted that these statutes and those are the statutes in Frontiero are not in any sense designed to rectify the effects of past discrimination against women citing Gruenwald versus Gardner and Jones versus Mayer and South Carolina versus Katzenbach.","start":1062.153,"stop":1085.488,"duration":23.34},{"text":"And, on the contrary, these statutes seize upon a group of women who have historically suffered discrimination in employment and rely on the effects of this past discrimination as a justification for heaping on additional economic disadvantages.","start":1085.488,"stop":1102.349,"duration":16.86},{"text":"That isn’t the case that we have here.","start":1102.349,"stop":1103.817,"duration":1.47},{"text":"There’s no -- there is -- I mean, the second is not the case that we have here.","start":1103.817,"stop":1110.081,"duration":6.26},{"text":"There is no purpose, nor result of heaping additional economic disadvantages on women.","start":1110.081,"stop":1115.914,"duration":5.83},{"text":"There is a purpose of taking affirmative action if indeed women are to be determined to be a suspect classification to reduce the results of past historic discrimination, so that even under Frontiero I would submit that it would be appropriate to approve this classification.","start":1115.914,"stop":1140.29,"duration":24.38},{"text":"However, I think it’s well to point out to the Court, and we submit, that this Court has, in general, limited suspect classifications to groups which sense that have been described since carrying products as discrete and insular minorities.","start":1140.29,"stop":1164.059,"duration":23.77},{"text":"And, I would submit that a classification based on sex does not have within it a discrete and insular minority whether be it the plaintiff here who is a male seeking to have the statute applied to him or else struck down all together.","start":1164.059,"stop":1188.068,"duration":24.01},{"text":"Clearly, the male is not a minority in a group where men and women are equal and if women are anything, it would be, I guess, a philosophical minority and that they’ve been discriminated against.","start":1188.068,"stop":1203.399,"duration":15.33},{"text":"But, I know of no case where the court has found that a philosophical minority qualifies for a strict scrutiny and I think it’s proper because any group that is an interest group is a minority and it may not get everything at once out of the judicial process and it’s not for the court, every time some group other than a racial classification or an easily identifiable classification like that comes before the court to give strict scrutiny to something that doesn’t -- to a statute that doesn’t give that interest group what it wants.","start":1203.399,"stop":1250.893,"duration":47.49},{"text":"And, on those grounds, Your Honor, I would submit that this classification should be upheld.","start":1250.893,"stop":1258.116,"duration":7.22}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKenzie.","start":1258.116,"stop":1258.975,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1258.975,"stop":1259.395,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is a property tax -- is this tax imposed on both real and personal property and as well as mixed or is this just a real property tax we’re talking about?","start":1259.395,"stop":1268.453,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- no, it’s a tax on both real and personal property.","start":1268.453,"stop":1275.721,"duration":7.27},{"text":"It’s on any ad valorem taxation which, in ad valorem taxes in Florida are both on real and personal property.","start":1275.721,"stop":1281.587,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Real and personal property.","start":1281.587,"stop":1282.969,"duration":1.38},{"text":"And how is it -- how is property appraised down there?","start":1282.969,"stop":1285.696,"duration":2.73},{"text":"How is it -- what’s the assessed evaluation?","start":1285.696,"stop":1288.477,"duration":2.78},{"text":"How close to realistic market value?","start":1288.477,"stop":1288.948,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s assessed at 100 -- by constitution, it’s to be assessed at full market value, 100%.","start":1288.948,"stop":1293.884,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what’s the practice?","start":1293.884,"stop":1295.367,"duration":1.48},{"text":"We all know about those constitutional issues.","start":1295.367,"stop":1296.245,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s in the court’s now as to whether in fact it is assessed at 100% of market value.","start":1296.245,"stop":1302.902,"duration":6.66},{"text":"In fact, it’s -- I would say, assessed between 80% and 100% of market value.","start":1302.902,"stop":1309.919,"duration":7.02},{"text":"That’s --","start":1309.919,"stop":1310.011,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it vary by counties?","start":1310.011,"stop":1311.457,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It varies by counties.","start":1311.457,"stop":1312.327,"duration":0.87},{"text":"That’s right.","start":1312.327,"stop":1312.401,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It usually does.","start":1312.401,"stop":1313.024,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The assessors of the counties do the assessing.","start":1313.024,"stop":1316.817,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So, this wouldn’t--","start":1316.817,"stop":1319.819,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"However, to add to that, all assessments are reviewed for the purpose of equalization by the Department of Revenue of the State of Florida.","start":1319.819,"stop":1327.354,"duration":7.54},{"text":"So that, theoretically, when they approve it, it’s a determination that that county is at 100% of assessed value.","start":1327.354,"stop":1335.189,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason for my question is, I was wondering whether this exemption could validly be supported as a provision where they might enable the widow to keep their family home after widowhood rather than having to sell it at a distressed sale if this were a real relief from the real estate taxes on that home.","start":1335.189,"stop":1358.355,"duration":23.17},{"text":"But, it hardly is enough, is it?","start":1358.355,"stop":1361.311,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question is really limited.","start":1361.311,"stop":1366.266,"duration":4.96},{"text":"It might be enough for one widow.","start":1366.266,"stop":1368.069,"duration":1.8},{"text":"It might not be enough for another.","start":1368.069,"stop":1369.563,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, $500 is -- and that’s the reason I asked how close to realistic market prices are your actual appraisals and assessments.","start":1369.563,"stop":1376.309,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"It is directly at 100% of assessed value, Your Honor.","start":1376.309,"stop":1378.653,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What’s your typical tax rate on real property, say, in Dade County?","start":1378.653,"stop":1385.222,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The rate would generally be 30 Mills which would translate into -- the 30 Mills would translate into a $15 exemption under this.","start":1385.222,"stop":1398.066,"duration":12.84}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on a house assessed at $20,000, what property tax would you pay in Dade County?","start":1398.066,"stop":1405.676,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":1405.676,"stop":1406.634,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"$600.","start":1406.634,"stop":1406.961,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"$600.","start":1406.961,"stop":1407.166,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"A month?","start":1407.166,"stop":1410.615,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"$600.","start":1410.615,"stop":1411.307,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"At 30 Mills, that $600.","start":1411.307,"stop":1412.573,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":1412.573,"stop":1415.936,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKenzie, in your brief you point out relying on Bureau of the Census figures that 35.8% of the families in Florida in which a female is a head of the family below the poverty level whereas, I think, about of about 9 --","start":1415.936,"stop":1438.661,"duration":22.73}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"7% --","start":1438.661,"stop":1439.108,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"9% of the men who had families --","start":1439.108,"stop":1443.062,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, Your Honor.","start":1443.062,"stop":1444.157,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Are below poverty level.","start":1444.157,"stop":1445.702,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right and I think that’s just --","start":1445.702,"stop":1447.16,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those figures unique to Florida or how would they be compared with national figures?","start":1447.16,"stop":1454.961,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I would imagine they would -- I really can’t answer that, Your Honor.","start":1454.961,"stop":1456.288,"duration":1.33},{"text":"Those figures were drawn out because we were especially concerned with the Florida situation.","start":1456.288,"stop":1460.855,"duration":4.57},{"text":"I imagine that they would probably be typical.","start":1460.855,"stop":1463.807,"duration":2.95},{"text":"I know of no situation in Florida that would make them a typical on a national basis, but I can’t represent that to the Court.","start":1463.807,"stop":1472.034,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you don’t have many of those owning homes, do you?","start":1472.034,"stop":1474.994,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":1474.994,"stop":1475.463,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t have many of those owning homes.","start":1475.463,"stop":1478.744,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The ones below the poverty level, Your Honor?","start":1478.744,"stop":1481.28,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they’re mostly renters, aren’t they?","start":1481.28,"stop":1483.547,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Not necessarily in Florida, Your Honor, because you have a lot of very poor people that own property and that they own mobile homes.","start":1483.547,"stop":1492.417,"duration":8.87},{"text":"That’s the typical situation in Florida.","start":1492.417,"stop":1494.316,"duration":1.9},{"text":"Much more so than any other state.","start":1494.316,"stop":1495.707,"duration":1.39},{"text":"I’d say a much larger percentage of those than in a typical state would be in a position where they were in property ownership.","start":1495.707,"stop":1503.863,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That wouldn’t be true up in the Turpentine area.","start":1503.863,"stop":1506.245,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m sorry?","start":1506.245,"stop":1506.981,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Up in the Turpentine area, up near the Georgia boarder.","start":1506.981,"stop":1510.694,"duration":3.71},{"text":"They don’t own anything up there.","start":1510.694,"stop":1512.549,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I live in the Turpentine area, Your Honor, and it’s not so much as the rest of the state but, certainly, it’s a mobile home area the same as the other part of the state, although it’s not so much of the elderly living there.","start":1512.549,"stop":1528.074,"duration":15.53},{"text":"So, that’s part of the problem.","start":1528.074,"stop":1531.695,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But it’s still at rage from the lower person to the highest anywhere you go.","start":1531.695,"stop":1536.321,"duration":4.63},{"text":"You admit that and I --","start":1536.321,"stop":1537.522,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1537.522,"stop":1539.881,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You say that’s normal for taxation and, in some areas, it is.","start":1539.881,"stop":1543.144,"duration":3.26},{"text":"It’s the question of whether it’s normal here where you draw the line on sex.","start":1543.144,"stop":1548.78,"duration":5.64},{"text":"Isn’t that the real problem?","start":1548.78,"stop":1549.361,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"We submit that this statute is a wreck.","start":1549.361,"stop":1553.91,"duration":4.55},{"text":"This statute and constitutional provision are a recognition of the economic realities of the State of Florida.","start":1553.91,"stop":1562.365,"duration":8.45},{"text":"Thank you, Gentlemen.","start":1562.365,"stop":1563.265,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. McKenzie.","start":1563.265,"stop":1564.698,"duration":1.43},{"text":"Mrs. Ginsburg, do you have anything further?","start":1564.698,"stop":1566.514,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I do.","start":1566.514,"stop":1568.681,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You have about two minutes remaining.","start":1568.681,"stop":1572.051,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"First, I would like to qualify that mobile homes are not subject to the ad valorem property tax.","start":1572.051,"stop":1577.723,"duration":5.67},{"text":"Article VII, Section 1 of the Constitution exempts, along with motor vehicles, mobile homes.","start":1577.723,"stop":1585.171,"duration":7.45},{"text":"Then, in --","start":1585.171,"stop":1585.706,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"With wheels or without?","start":1585.706,"stop":1587.377,"duration":1.67},{"text":"This probably isn’t very important but I know in many states there’s an argument about what is a mobile home.","start":1587.377,"stop":1591.89,"duration":4.51},{"text":"After it comes to rest --","start":1591.89,"stop":1592.759,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1592.759,"stop":1593.137,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And if the wheels come off it, is it still a mobile home?","start":1593.137,"stop":1595.724,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Also, I would like to qualify the statement made that this tax is subject -- real property and personal property are subject to this tax.","start":1595.724,"stop":1604.539,"duration":8.82},{"text":"That’s true in the constitutional description, but a statute exempts all household goods and all personal effects for all persons whether or not they’re heads of family, and that’s Florida statute 196.181.","start":1604.539,"stop":1618.947,"duration":14.41},{"text":"In fact, the legislature has twice extended this constitutional provision that we’re talking about by ordinary statute.","start":1618.947,"stop":1627.446,"duration":8.5},{"text":"And then, finally, with respect to a point that came out yesterday, recent models for the disposition that appellant seeks in this case include the per curiam opinion last term in New Jersey Welfare Rights Organization against Cahill and early on, Mr. Justice Blackmun’s opinion in Graham against Richardson.","start":1627.446,"stop":1646.404,"duration":18.96},{"text":"Both of those opinions dealt with constitutionally under-inclusive state rather than federal benefit statutes, and both are cited at page 27 of our main brief and in a footnote at page 8 of our reply brief.","start":1646.404,"stop":1662.147,"duration":15.74}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Professor Ginsburg, could I ask a question.","start":1662.147,"stop":1666.982,"duration":4.84},{"text":"You’re familiar with the DeFunis case to be argued this afternoon?","start":1666.982,"stop":1670.83,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1670.83,"stop":1673.734,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"This, perhaps, is an unfair question but does your position in this case with respect to the Florida classifications bear in any way on the issues in DeFunis?","start":1673.734,"stop":1688.299,"duration":14.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all.","start":1688.299,"stop":1690.064,"duration":1.77},{"text":"The DeFunis case raises a very different issue.","start":1690.064,"stop":1693.746,"duration":3.68},{"text":"DeFunis is a program of a law school that is designed to open doors to equal opportunity, to assure a law student body with diverse backgrounds and experience and to what defy the conspicuous absence of minority groups in the profession.","start":1693.746,"stop":1715.711,"duration":21.96},{"text":"It is not a welfare, though assumed, based on the assumed inferior capabilities of any population group.","start":1715.711,"stop":1724.356,"duration":8.64},{"text":"No rigid race line is presented, as we have here, a rigid sex line.","start":1724.356,"stop":1728.627,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Race is merely one of the many characteristics assessed in that case.","start":1728.627,"stop":1732.303,"duration":3.68},{"text":"But most significantly, DeFunis involves no general law classification.","start":1732.303,"stop":1737.674,"duration":5.37},{"text":"It’s a measure addressed to very special selection problem that law schools have.","start":1737.674,"stop":1743.259,"duration":5.59},{"text":"Law schools have the very hard task of choosing some from among many applicants that are fit to pursue their educational program.","start":1743.259,"stop":1752.383,"duration":9.12},{"text":"By contrast, here we are dealing with the law, general application of the law with respect to property owners where there can be no justification for the crude device of labeling any group: racial, ethnic, or sexual as needy persons.","start":1752.383,"stop":1767.501,"duration":15.12},{"text":"And, income tax is readily available to a legislature that wishes to distinguish on the basis of need, and immutable birth characteristic should be irrelevant for general law purposes.","start":1767.501,"stop":1783.654,"duration":16.15}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mrs. Ginsburg.","start":1783.654,"stop":1785.267,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1785.267,"stop":1786.343,"duration":1.08},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1786.343,"stop":1788.582,"duration":2.24}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 25, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/17024","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in 73-78, Kahn against Shevin.","start":0,"stop":58.408,"duration":58.41},{"text":"Mrs. Ginsburg, you may proceed whenever you’re ready.","start":58.408,"stop":62.228,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice --","start":62.228,"stop":63.188,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"If you’d like to lower the lectern, you’ve quite the liberty to do so","start":63.188,"stop":75.329,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":75.329,"stop":79.473,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Appellant Mel Kahn, a Florida resident is a widower.","start":79.473,"stop":86.166,"duration":6.69},{"text":"In January 1971, based on his status as a surviving spouse, he applied to the Dade County Tax Assessor for a property tax exemption.","start":86.166,"stop":99.211,"duration":13.05},{"text":"The statute under which widower Kahn sought exemption provided, a widow, along with the disabled persons is entitled to exempt $500 yearly from her property tax.","start":99.211,"stop":115.068,"duration":15.86},{"text":"Mel Khan was denied the claimed exemption solely on the ground of his sex.","start":115.068,"stop":120.962,"duration":5.89},{"text":"Requesting judicial review, he alleged that the statute under which he claimed exemption have been interpreted and applied in conflict with the equal protection guarantee of the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":120.962,"stop":135.173,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually he didn’t allege that in the trial, didn’t he expressly say he didn’t want to raise this federal question there?","start":135.173,"stop":140.756,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"In the original complaint, he suggested that he might save at the federal question till a later time but then the federal question was raised and decided with the agreement of all parties.","start":140.756,"stop":150.92,"duration":10.16}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But he didn’t simply say he might say but he said he wanted to say that, didn’t he?","start":150.92,"stop":155.565,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":155.565,"stop":155.918,"duration":0.35},{"text":"But apparently, with the understanding of the court and the agreement of both sides, the federal question was heard and decided both in the trial court and in the Florida Supreme Court.","start":155.918,"stop":172.329,"duration":16.41},{"text":"Appellant sought a declaration that the exemption provision is unconstitutional insofar as it excludes widowers.","start":172.329,"stop":181.487,"duration":9.16},{"text":"On cross motions for summary judgment, the Court of First Instance held that the statute by according exemption to all widows and excluding all widowers discriminated arbitrarily between widowed persons and therefore violated the equal protection guarantees of the State and Federal Constitution.","start":181.487,"stop":203.904,"duration":22.42},{"text":"On appeal, the Florida Supreme Court reversed.","start":203.904,"stop":207.228,"duration":3.32},{"text":"The Florida Supreme Court held that the distinction between surviving spouses though based solely on gender did not deny to any person the equal protection of the laws.","start":207.228,"stop":219.418,"duration":12.19},{"text":"It is appellant’s position that the gender based distinction upheld by the Florida Supreme Court discriminates invidiously in two respects.","start":219.418,"stop":230.839,"duration":11.42},{"text":"First, most obviously, it discriminates against men who have lost their wives more subtly but as surely it discounts the contribution made to the marital unit and the family academy by the female partner for her death, occasions no exemption for the surviving spouse.","start":230.839,"stop":253.309,"duration":22.47},{"text":"By defining the exempt person as widow, rather than surviving spouse, this provision now covering the blind and the totally disabled along with the widow is keen to a classification delineated by the president of one of our nation’s leading educational institutions.","start":253.309,"stop":275.01,"duration":21.7},{"text":"Anticipating an increase in conscription not too many years ago, this distinguished educator complained, “We shall be left with the blind, the lame, and the women.”","start":275.01,"stop":289.151,"duration":14.14},{"text":"This Court’s decision in Reed v. Reed 404 U.S. and its judgment in Frontiero v. Richardson 411 U.S. indicate genuine concern to analyze sex classifications free from the generalizations of the Victorian age.","start":289.151,"stop":307.539,"duration":18.39},{"text":"Appellant maintains that the Reed standard is not met by a surviving spouse, tax exemption that uses gender as the sole criterion for qualification or if need is the concern then sex should not be a substitute for an income test.","start":307.539,"stop":326.724,"duration":19.19},{"text":"And if widowed state is the concern, then it is irrational to distinguish between taxpayers based on their sex.","start":326.724,"stop":335.541,"duration":8.82},{"text":"Far from constituting a rational shorthand but distinguishing between taxpayers on the basis of need or life situation.","start":335.541,"stop":343.553,"duration":8.01},{"text":"A widow’s only classification is a crude device that originated in and today perpetuates Victorian assumptions concerning the station of men and women.","start":343.553,"stop":357.655,"duration":14.1},{"text":"To resolve this case, the Court need not go beyond the scrutiny employed in Reed and followed by the Tenth Circuit in Moritz v. Commissioner 469 F. 2d.","start":357.655,"stop":371.05,"duration":13.4},{"text":"The decision in Reed and the judgment in Frontiero indicate the Court’s clear willingness to give sex classifications more than surface examination.","start":371.05,"stop":384.531,"duration":13.48},{"text":"However, if the Court wants to consider application of a suspect classification doctrine then it must face the fact that problems of race and sex discrimination are often different and that neither women nor blacks are aided by lumping the two together for all purposes.","start":384.531,"stop":410.023,"duration":25.49},{"text":"Thus far, this Court has applied the label suspect classification only in opinions involving discrimination, hostile to groups not dominant in society.","start":410.023,"stop":423.513,"duration":13.49},{"text":"But whatever may be said for a one-way suspect classification doctrine in cases involving racial discrimination, a one-way approach in sex discrimination cases would be fought with danger for women because of the historic tendency of jurors to rationalize any special treatment of women as benignly in their favor.","start":423.513,"stop":450.133,"duration":26.62},{"text":"With respect to race, the effects of officially sanctioned segregation are still very much with us but complex doctrines directed to the continuing impact of racial segregation are not necessarily applicable to sex discrimination.","start":450.133,"stop":470.379,"duration":20.25},{"text":"The difference is perhaps best illustrated with respect to the educational experience.","start":470.379,"stop":476.526,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Most public education is co-educational though females have been segregated and restricted in some areas, most notably vocational training and athletics.","start":476.526,"stop":490.539,"duration":14.01},{"text":"But generally, females participate with males in academic programs, in elementary and high school and in fact, tend to do better there than males.","start":490.539,"stop":503.823,"duration":13.28},{"text":"For many females, this record of achievement continues into college and university.","start":503.823,"stop":509.051,"duration":5.23},{"text":"For example, females outscore males on the law school admissions test.","start":509.051,"stop":516.448,"duration":7.4},{"text":"The problem for women is that along the way, an attitude is instilled insidiously.","start":516.448,"stop":524.985,"duration":8.54},{"text":"This attitude is described in a nutshell in graffiti etched on a college library carrel in the early 1950s.","start":524.985,"stop":536.795,"duration":11.81},{"text":"The epigram reads, “Study hard, get good grades, get your degree, get married, have three kids, die, and be buried.”","start":536.795,"stop":552.081,"duration":15.29},{"text":"From the first drop line, the sex of the writer is impossible to determine from the second, her sex is impossible to mistake.","start":552.081,"stop":563.103,"duration":11.02},{"text":"To cure the problem, thought so acutely by the young woman who wrote those words and so many others like her, the law must stop using sex as a shorthand for functional description.","start":563.103,"stop":575.788,"duration":12.69},{"text":"It must deal with the parent not the mother, with the homemaker not the housewife, and with the surviving spouse not the widow.","start":575.788,"stop":587.551,"duration":11.76},{"text":"To appreciate the character of the challenged classification, the widow’s only exemption must be viewed in historical context.","start":587.551,"stop":596.041,"duration":8.49},{"text":"The exemption became part of Florida’s law in 1885.","start":596.041,"stop":600.43,"duration":4.39},{"text":"At that time, indeed, well into the 20th century, Florida Law routinely differentiated between the roles of men and women and particularly married men and married women.","start":600.43,"stop":613.084,"duration":12.65},{"text":"Women could not vote nor did they serve on juries for example.","start":613.084,"stop":617.814,"duration":4.73},{"text":"Well, past the middle of the 20th century, in fact up till 1968, a Florida married woman could not transfer even her own interest in real property without her husband’s consent.","start":617.814,"stop":632.035,"duration":14.22},{"text":"Not surprisingly, the married woman was deemed worthy of special solicitude.","start":632.035,"stop":637.719,"duration":5.68},{"text":"On the death of the person, the law regarded as her guardian, her superior not her peer.","start":637.719,"stop":647.28,"duration":9.56},{"text":"While the widows only exemption was designed with the 19th century status of married woman in mind.","start":647.28,"stop":653.461,"duration":6.18},{"text":"The Florida Supreme Court found contemporary justification for it in this unquestionable fact.","start":653.461,"stop":660.7,"duration":7.24},{"text":"Women workers as a class do not earn as much as man.","start":660.7,"stop":665.847,"duration":5.15},{"text":"This well known and still wide earnings gap according to the Florida Supreme Court supplies a fair and substantial basis for the tax classification widow rather than surviving spouse.","start":665.847,"stop":681.704,"duration":15.86},{"text":"But beyond doubt, a widow’s only exemption has no impact whatever on the conditions responsible for the earnings gap.","start":681.704,"stop":689.711,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not clear.","start":689.711,"stop":691.844,"duration":2.13},{"text":"You are arguing that sex ought not to be treated as a suspect classification?","start":691.844,"stop":696.747,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I am arguing that if first, that it is not necessary to deal with that question in this case.","start":696.747,"stop":703.422,"duration":6.68},{"text":"But second, that if sex is treated as a suspect classification which I think properly it is, then the Court must be aware that the arguments that we give special scrutiny only to lines that appear to disfavoring women will be ultimately harmful to women because the history has been --","start":703.422,"stop":726.937,"duration":23.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So it’s suspect class?","start":726.937,"stop":728.609,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the classification.","start":728.609,"stop":729.994,"duration":1.38},{"text":"It is the criterion sex that is suspect.","start":729.994,"stop":733.045,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Not female but the criterion sex.","start":733.045,"stop":736.397,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally, isn’t it the fact that the Court has found classification to be suspect when it involves a discriminatory classification against a minority group?","start":736.397,"stop":750.21,"duration":13.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":750.21,"stop":750.948,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that accurate?","start":750.948,"stop":752.842,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"In this Court’s precedent, the suspect label has been used --","start":752.842,"stop":755.7,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the paradigm is race?","start":755.7,"stop":758.241,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and national --","start":758.241,"stop":759.136,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) minority race?","start":759.136,"stop":761.167,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":761.167,"stop":762.342,"duration":1.17},{"text":"And what was looked at --","start":762.342,"stop":763.456,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Alienage is another?","start":763.456,"stop":765.393,"duration":1.94},{"text":"Possibly, right?","start":765.393,"stop":766.989,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Alienage, yes.","start":766.989,"stop":767.871,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So the suspect classification is not only with respect to discriminatory classification against a minority group, is that correct?","start":767.871,"stop":775.448,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That is how it has been used in this Court’s precedent.","start":775.448,"stop":777.817,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Traditionally, up till now?","start":777.817,"stop":778.905,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":778.905,"stop":779.117,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And your point, I gather, is that I don’t know if you mentioned it but women first of all are not a minority group, and secondly, since courts have been in the habit to view any classification of women as beneficent --","start":779.117,"stop":793.977,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":793.977,"stop":795.813,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- provision of course should be on guard and not --","start":795.813,"stop":799.219,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, my point is that the women – what will aid woman most is not looking to see whether a classification is benign or invidious but whether it is a sex criterion, as a shorthand for what should be a functional criteria.","start":799.219,"stop":814.157,"duration":14.94}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":814.157,"stop":815.165,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, you don’t want it whether it helps -- even when it helps?","start":815.165,"stop":818.783,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"My question is if it ever does one.","start":818.783,"stop":821.11,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Yes.","start":821.11,"stop":822.372,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But even if it does, you would assume on that assumption --","start":822.372,"stop":825.527,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But I have not yet found any such classification in the law that genuinely helps from the very short-sided view point perhaps such as this one?","start":825.527,"stop":836.869,"duration":11.34},{"text":"Yes.","start":836.869,"stop":839.435,"duration":2.57},{"text":"But long run?","start":839.435,"stop":842.954,"duration":3.52},{"text":"No.","start":842.954,"stop":843.376,"duration":0.42},{"text":"I think that what women need is first of all a removal of exclusions and restricted quotas.","start":843.376,"stop":850.832,"duration":7.46},{"text":"They are the only population group that today still faces outright exclusions and restrictive quotas and then what is necessary is the welcome sign.","start":850.832,"stop":861.521,"duration":10.69},{"text":"A notice that in the professions, in trades and occupations women are now as welcomed as men.","start":861.521,"stop":871.032,"duration":9.51},{"text":"But the notion that they need special favored treatment because they are women I think has been – what has helped to keep women in a special place, and has kept them away from equal opportunity for so long.","start":871.032,"stop":885.36,"duration":14.33},{"text":"In other words, take this exemption.","start":885.36,"stop":887.3,"duration":1.94},{"text":"It’s not the purpose of this exemption to eliminate discrimination against women.","start":887.3,"stop":891.817,"duration":4.52},{"text":"It isn’t the purpose to eliminate discrimination in pay or to equalize training, study, job opportunities for them.","start":891.817,"stop":908.585,"duration":16.77},{"text":"In contrast to these widows exemption are measures that are realistically designed to promote equal opportunity free from gender based discrimination, Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 for example.","start":908.585,"stop":923.433,"duration":14.85},{"text":"These measures focus on eliminating sex typing of this very order as the essential task.","start":923.433,"stop":930.735,"duration":7.3},{"text":"Nor, can an exemption of this kind be regarded as a rational welfare measure to alleviate the effects of past discrimination against women.","start":930.735,"stop":940.373,"duration":9.64},{"text":"As a welfare measure, supposedly directed to the authority of women property owners to pay taxes, the exemption is incredibly designed that encompasses the independently wealthy widow and at the same time it excludes the women who encounters perhaps the sharpest discrimination.","start":940.373,"stop":958.718,"duration":18.34},{"text":"The female had a household who never marry and some, the classification is obviously unrelated to any biological difference between men and women.","start":958.718,"stop":969.765,"duration":11.05},{"text":"It is not fairly and substantially related to the need or life situation of the individual men or women but it is very much related to underestimation of the women’s contribution to the family economy.","start":969.765,"stop":983.393,"duration":13.63},{"text":"Significantly, the Florida Supreme Court on other days has demonstrated its understanding of the very real and substantial economic contribution made by the female partner whether it’s homemaker to gainful employment or as increasingly the case through productive effort both in and outside the home.","start":983.393,"stop":1005.159,"duration":21.77},{"text":"In --","start":1005.159,"stop":1005.573,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But insofar as the statute does not differentiate among various widows or various categories of widows.","start":1005.573,"stop":1013.846,"duration":8.27},{"text":"It’s very typical of tax legislation generally, isn’t it?","start":1013.846,"stop":1017.799,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the --","start":1017.799,"stop":1018.597,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean certainly, the federal income tax which gives every taxpayer an exemption of $750 for each dependent regardless of his circumstances or the dependents’ circumstances.","start":1018.597,"stop":1030.037,"duration":11.44},{"text":"If he is below certain age, he is certainly very blunt instrument.","start":1030.037,"stop":1034.388,"duration":4.35},{"text":"And insofar as this --","start":1034.388,"stop":1035.204,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1035.204,"stop":1035.5,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as this legislation fails to discriminate as among various categories of widows, you don’t really attack it, do you?","start":1035.5,"stop":1046.394,"duration":10.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The classification surviving spouse is well-known classification in both state and federal tax law.","start":1046.394,"stop":1053.898,"duration":7.5},{"text":"It does reflect the legislature’s recognition that loss of a spouse is a unique episode in a person’s life and I am not challenging the classification surviving spouse.","start":1053.898,"stop":1066.309,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"No, my point was.","start":1066.309,"stop":1067.299,"duration":0.99},{"text":"Perhaps, I didn’t express it very well.","start":1067.299,"stop":1068.757,"duration":1.46},{"text":"You, a few moments ago, spoke and said that the legislation is applicable whether the widow be a millionairess or whether she be a poor working widow or whether she had children or no children, and so on.","start":1068.757,"stop":1083.507,"duration":14.75},{"text":"I didn’t really understand that your basic attack upon this legislation was premised upon that fact.","start":1083.507,"stop":1088.416,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":1088.416,"stop":1089.125,"duration":0.71},{"text":"I am not suggesting that the tax assessor call in each individual exempt person and see if that person really needs the exemption, not at all.","start":1089.125,"stop":1095.931,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think so.","start":1095.931,"stop":1096.435,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But I am suggesting is that the sex criterion is invalid.","start":1096.435,"stop":1101.193,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Ginsburg, assume and argue that being said -- how do you get into relief in this case?","start":1101.193,"stop":1108.345,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1108.345,"stop":1108.574,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming that we declare the statute unconstitutional.","start":1108.574,"stop":1112.386,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1112.386,"stop":1112.765,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Well, if this Court --","start":1112.765,"stop":1113.59,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Who gets any relief then?","start":1113.59,"stop":1116.13,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mel Khan gets the tax exemption for the tax year in question.","start":1116.13,"stop":1121.552,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How?","start":1121.552,"stop":1124.062,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"First, --","start":1124.062,"stop":1124.785,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I said, if we declare the statute unconstitutional.","start":1124.785,"stop":1128.119,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar as it discriminates against widowers, I think that, if you declare the gender line unconstitutional which is the only thing that the Court has been requested to do, then the Florida Supreme Court should be free to consider where the total demolition of this exemption or repairing it to fit the Constitutional requirements is preferred.","start":1128.119,"stop":1149.659,"duration":21.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming that they just ended and nobody gets other than --","start":1149.659,"stop":1155.382,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"For the future.","start":1155.382,"stop":1156.616,"duration":1.23},{"text":"Widower concept is exemption --","start":1156.616,"stop":1157.243,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does this case in this Court which says that that’s not for the courts to do the case of Cummings (ph) against the Board of Education in Georgia 1914 or so.","start":1157.243,"stop":1171.288,"duration":14.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I am sorry that I am not familiar with that.","start":1171.288,"stop":1173.436,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it’s a case where -- it’s just like this, you want to knock out and then this Court said that if you do that and nobody gets anything, that’s not the proper place with equity court to act.","start":1173.436,"stop":1188.337,"duration":14.9}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I am asking this Court to take the same approach that was taken in Frontiero last semester, where a group of service spouses, in that case husbands, did not qualify for the exemption because the statute excluded them and all this Court held was that the state was unconstitutional insofar as it excluded that class.","start":1188.337,"stop":1212.57,"duration":24.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And this Court has plenty of jurisdictions over the federal jurisdiction over the federal army?","start":1212.57,"stop":1219.225,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but ultimately --","start":1219.225,"stop":1220.366,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And we do not have it on the State of Florida.","start":1220.366,"stop":1223.752,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Ultimately, of course that is a question for the Florida Supreme Court to answer and it can answer that question for itself.","start":1223.752,"stop":1232.134,"duration":8.38},{"text":"But it would be --","start":1232.134,"stop":1232.442,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you’d be perfectly satisfied if the end result of this case is that would it get nothing?","start":1232.442,"stop":1238.041,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not think that that would be the reasonable approach for either the Florida Supreme Court or the Florida legislature to take.","start":1238.041,"stop":1248.146,"duration":10.11},{"text":"There’s a Florida problem here that --","start":1248.146,"stop":1249.915,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course if everybody – if the end result is that everybody is the exemption that’s the same as nobody getting an exemption.","start":1249.915,"stop":1256.343,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That all widowed persons get the exemption and we’re talking about a very small addition, since there are about four times as many widows.","start":1256.343,"stop":1263.505,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Many more widows than widowers.","start":1263.505,"stop":1263.979,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in Florida as widowers I suppose that a reasonable legislature looking at that logic class and wanting the exemption for that logic class would extend it to this much smaller group by than (Voice Overlap)","start":1263.979,"stop":1276.73,"duration":12.75}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"My brother Marshall suggests that is the question ultimately up to the Supreme Court and/or legislature of Florida.","start":1276.73,"stop":1283.353,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s quite correct.","start":1283.353,"stop":1284.385,"duration":1.03},{"text":"Yes.","start":1284.385,"stop":1285.183,"duration":0.8},{"text":"All we ask of this Court --","start":1285.183,"stop":1285.897,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Unlike Frontiero in that respect.","start":1285.897,"stop":1287.567,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"We ask this Court to declare the statute defective in that it excludes widowers, and the remaining relief would be inappropriate question for the Florida Supreme Court.","start":1287.567,"stop":1299.167,"duration":11.6}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Ginsburg, pursuing this discussion, do I understand you to say that the Florida court would have not only authority but I think on page 26 of your brief you said it’s a responsible court it would in effect rewrite this statute contrary to what you concede to be as plain language and intent that a court would do that rather than the Florida legislation?","start":1299.167,"stop":1326.697,"duration":27.53}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The court has two choices in that situation.","start":1326.697,"stop":1330.545,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It can either nullify the statute in which case it is totally toward the legislature’s will or it can modify the statute to meet the constitutional equal protection requirement.","start":1330.545,"stop":1342.388,"duration":11.84},{"text":"If it guesses the wrong way in either direction, the legislature of course has the final word.","start":1342.388,"stop":1348.876,"duration":6.49},{"text":"But the court faced with the question, should we take this exemption away from the three quarters of the population, the widow population that now gets it, rather than extend it to the one-quarter that doesn’t in order to preserve what the legislature did do.","start":1348.876,"stop":1364.91,"duration":16.03},{"text":"It seems to me, it’s eminently more destructive of the legislative will to say that we remove this exemption altogether than to say we’ll keep what you wanted and then just add this much smaller group.","start":1364.91,"stop":1379.586,"duration":14.68}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I might agree with that.","start":1379.586,"stop":1381.249,"duration":1.66},{"text":"Excuse Mr. Chief Justice, I am going to say I could be persuaded, I think, to agree that it would be more constructive if you prevail here for the legislation in the end to equalize it.","start":1381.249,"stop":1395.966,"duration":14.72},{"text":"But I was curious by your suggestion that the court itself could rewrite a perfectly plain statute conceded by you to be plain.","start":1395.966,"stop":1406.379,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"A number of state courts have done just that.","start":1406.379,"stop":1408.595,"duration":2.22},{"text":"We have cited Small against Feezy (ph) for example.","start":1408.595,"stop":1410.796,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We gone that far but I didn’t know it gone that far?","start":1410.796,"stop":1414.677,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"These were all cases where a statute was constitutionally infirm because of under inclusion.","start":1414.677,"stop":1421.747,"duration":7.07},{"text":"A group had been left out and then it was the court’s choice to determine whether it wanted to knock out the provision altogether or to do well as Mr. Justice Harlan once pointed, the choice is between amputation and a skin graft.","start":1421.747,"stop":1440.74,"duration":18.99}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s what he suggest in Welsh but --","start":1440.74,"stop":1442.377,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1442.377,"stop":1442.561,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this Court has never done that, has it?","start":1442.561,"stop":1445.391,"duration":2.83},{"text":"That was his point of view?","start":1445.391,"stop":1446.289,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That was a concurring opinion --","start":1446.289,"stop":1448.115,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1448.115,"stop":1448.535,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Well, that was the Fifth vote in determining this.","start":1448.535,"stop":1451.043,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1451.043,"stop":1451.856,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's definitely, I gather you recognize.","start":1451.856,"stop":1455.47,"duration":3.61},{"text":"You suggested at page 25 of your brief that if we agree that the statute is unconstitutional that we should remand for consideration whether consistent with the dominant legislative purpose constitutional infirmity this should be remedied by holding the exemption available to all widowed property owners.","start":1455.47,"stop":1472.579,"duration":17.11},{"text":"We wouldn’t do that but we only would do --","start":1472.579,"stop":1474.961,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It will be my --","start":1474.961,"stop":1475.78,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It will be simply remand from proceedings not inconsistent --","start":1475.78,"stop":1478.784,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly right.","start":1478.784,"stop":1479.762,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- without making any suggestion.","start":1479.762,"stop":1481.011,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s quite so.","start":1481.011,"stop":1482.044,"duration":1.03},{"text":"Yes.","start":1482.044,"stop":1484.121,"duration":2.08},{"text":"What we seek in this Court is a declaration of the gender line is unconstitutional, that it is unconstitutional to exclude widowers, and then a remand before the proceedings not inconsistent with that opinion.","start":1484.121,"stop":1497.292,"duration":13.17}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the only way we could do it or could we simply say the statute is invalid.","start":1497.292,"stop":1503.049,"duration":5.76},{"text":"If we --","start":1503.049,"stop":1504.239,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that you would be clearer and provide more precise instruction to the Florida Supreme Court if you said that the statute was unconstitutional insofar as it excluded widowers.","start":1504.239,"stop":1516.956,"duration":12.72}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1516.956,"stop":1519.435,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You take the risk of you, I am speaking in broad terms, a litigant takes the risk of destroying an entire statutory scheme, when they attack it in this Court as one of the risks, is that not so?","start":1519.435,"stop":1535.37,"duration":15.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Brandeis once made that point that when a taxpayer is in this situation.","start":1535.37,"stop":1540.372,"duration":5},{"text":"That taxpayer cannot be expected to have a situation equalize by asking the taxpayer to increase the taxes of others similarly situated.","start":1540.372,"stop":1551.965,"duration":11.59},{"text":"So that when a taxpayer is subject to a discriminatory tax through favoring others.","start":1551.965,"stop":1560.265,"duration":8.3},{"text":"The only equalization possible is to grant that taxpayer the exemption afforded to others and then change for the future can be made so that all persons similarly situated will either be included or excluded from the exemption.","start":1560.265,"stop":1576.342,"duration":16.08}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don’t -- you still -- we cannot do that.","start":1576.342,"stop":1580.693,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it’s the province of the Florida Supreme Court to decide what should be done with that Florida statute.","start":1580.693,"stop":1585.982,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But are we obliged to suggest to them what they should do or can we do anything more than hold that statute unconstitutional?","start":1585.982,"stop":1594.138,"duration":8.16},{"text":"Can we do anything more?","start":1594.138,"stop":1596.287,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you can do what Justice Brandeis suggested in the Iowa-Des Moines case 284 U.S. and that is to say that this appellant must be granted the exemption because there is no other way that his claim of the denial of equal protection can be redressed.","start":1596.287,"stop":1616.747,"duration":20.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is entirely different from this case?","start":1616.747,"stop":1621.451,"duration":4.7},{"text":"The exemption in that case is --","start":1621.451,"stop":1623.081,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn’t a different kind of exemption but the same situation that --","start":1623.081,"stop":1627.646,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not a member.","start":1627.646,"stop":1631.074,"duration":3.43},{"text":"But wouldn’t we be rewriting the statute?","start":1631.074,"stop":1633.719,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you wouldn’t be rewriting the statute.","start":1633.719,"stop":1635.646,"duration":1.93},{"text":"You would be holding that the statute contains a constitutional defect at the classification.","start":1635.646,"stop":1642.348,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1642.348,"stop":1642.774,"duration":0.43},{"text":"If we say that you must include the others.","start":1642.774,"stop":1645.789,"duration":3.02},{"text":"We wouldn’t be rewriting the statute?","start":1645.789,"stop":1647.811,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You would not be rewriting the statute for anyone other than our claimant who made a timely claim for this exemption and whose denial -- to whom the denial of equal protection cannot be redressed in any other way.","start":1647.811,"stop":1662.632,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Or that a minor repair of the statute?","start":1662.632,"stop":1666.481,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Would call the extension of the statute to widowers a minor repair.","start":1666.481,"stop":1671.268,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Yes.","start":1671.268,"stop":1671.729,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Necessary repair.","start":1671.729,"stop":1673.678,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"A necessary repair to preserve its constitutionality.","start":1673.678,"stop":1676.531,"duration":2.85},{"text":"Yes.","start":1676.531,"stop":1681.735,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we’ll not ask you to spend one minute dividing your argument counsel.","start":1681.735,"stop":1685.46,"duration":3.73},{"text":"We’ll let you start fresh in the morning.","start":1685.46,"stop":1687.244,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Sydney H. McKenzie, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Pretty good, Your Honor.","start":1687.244,"stop":1690.058,"duration":2.81}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Feb  25 - 26, 1974","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"73-78","citation":"416 US 351 (1974)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/416/351","lowerCourt":"Florida Supreme Court","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Apr 24, 1974"}